# Deno 2.x Conventions

## Imports

Use the import map in `deno.json` — never write bare `npm:` or `jsr:` specifiers inline:

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
import { assertEquals } from "jsr:@std/assert@^1";
import { generateText } from "npm:ai";

// ✅ GOOD
import { assertEquals } from "@std/assert";
import { generateText } from "ai";
```

## Standard Library

Prefer `@std/` packages over third-party alternatives:

- `@std/assert` for test assertions (not chai/jest expect)
- `@std/path` for path manipulation (not path-browserify)
- `@std/fs` for file system helpers

## Tests

Use `Deno.test()` — not Jest, Vitest, or Mocha:

```typescript
// ✅ GOOD
Deno.test("description", () => {
  assertEquals(actual, expected);
});
```

Test files are named `*_test.ts`. Run with `deno task test`.

## Permissions

Always use the minimum required permissions. Specify them explicitly in tasks:

```
--allow-net   // network access
--allow-env   // environment variable access
--allow-read  // file system reads
--allow-write // file system writes
```

## Environment Variables

Load `.env` via the `--env-file` flag (built into Deno 2) — no `@std/dotenv` needed.
Validate variables at startup using `getEnv()` from `shared/env.ts`.

## Module Conventions

- Keep entry points thin (`main.ts`) — they validate env and orchestrate
- Put pure logic in separate files for testability (e.g. `chat.ts`)
- Use dependency injection for external services (pass `model` as a parameter)
- Shared utilities live in `shared/`

## Tasks

Run common operations via `deno.json` tasks:

```bash
deno task chat        # run the OpenAI chat script
deno task test        # run all tests
deno task fmt         # auto-format
deno task check       # fmt + lint + typecheck
deno task setup-hooks # activate pre-commit hook (once after cloning)
```
